Rakie Kim <rakie.kim@sk.com>

[RFC PATCH 0/4] mm/mempolicy: introduce socket-aware weighted interleave

The concept is sound and the benchmark numbers are compelling.
A few correctness issues need attention before this is ready.

--- [RFC PATCH 1/4] mm/numa: introduce nearest_nodes_nodemask() ---

> diff --git a/include/linux/numa.h b/include/linux/numa.h
> +static inline int nearest_nodes_nodemask(int node, const nodemask_t *mask,
> +					 nodemask_t *out)
> +{
> +	return 0;
> +}

The !CONFIG_NUMA stub returns 0 (success) without touching *out.
Any caller that trusts the return code and then reads *out will use
uninitialized stack memory.  The stub should clear *out via
nodes_clear(*out) before returning, matching the real implementation's
behavior on an empty mask.

Minor: nearest_nodes_nodemask() is a NUMA topology utility declared
in include/linux/numa.h but implemented in mm/mempolicy.c.  The
existing nearest_node_nodemask() sets this precedent, but it is still
an odd home for a generic NUMA helper.

--- [RFC PATCH 2/4] mm/memory-tiers: introduce socket-aware topology ---

> diff --git a/include/linux/memory-tiers.h b/include/linux/memory-tiers.h

[ ... ]

> +static inline int mp_next_demotion_node(int nid)
> +{
> +	return 0;
> +}
> +
> +static inline int mp_next_promotion_node(int nid)
> +{
> +	return 0;
> +}

These stubs return 0, but 0 is a valid NUMA node number.  Callers that
use the return value as a demotion or promotion target will think node 0
is always a valid target, even when no demotion policy is configured.
The existing next_demotion_node() stub returns NUMA_NO_NODE for exactly
this reason.  mp_next_demotion_node() and mp_next_promotion_node() must
do the same.

> +static inline int mp_get_package_nodes(int nid, nodemask_t *out)
> +{
> +	return 0;
> +}
> +
> +static inline int mp_get_package_cpu_nodes(int nid, nodemask_t *out)
> +{
> +	return 0;
> +}
> +
> +static inline int mp_get_package_memory_only_nodes(int nid, nodemask_t *out)
> +{
> +	return 0;
> +}

Same problem: all three return 0 (success) without initializing *out.
A caller that checks the return value and then reads *out gets garbage.
These stubs should set *out = NODE_MASK_NONE before returning.

--- [RFC PATCH 4/4] mm/mempolicy: enhance weighted interleave ---

> +static int policy_resolve_package_nodes(struct mempolicy *policy,
> +					nodemask_t *mask)
> +{

[ ... ]

> +		if (nodes_empty(*mask)) {
> +			node = first_node(policy->nodes);
> +			ret = mp_get_package_nodes(node, &package_mask);
> +			if (ret)
> +				goto out;
> +			nodes_and(*mask, package_mask, policy->nodes);
> +			if (nodes_empty(*mask))
> +				goto out;
> +		}
> +	}
> +
> +out:
> +	return ret;

When the final nodes_and() yields an empty *mask, the code falls
through to "out" with ret still 0 (success) but *mask empty.  The
caller in weighted_interleave_nodes() only gates on a non-zero return:

  if (policy_resolve_package_nodes(policy, &mask))
      mask = policy->nodes;

So an empty mask slips through undetected.  The subsequent
next_node_in(node, empty_mask) returns MAX_NUMNODES, which then
propagates up through mempolicy_slab_node() and policy_nodemask()
as an invalid node number.

Reaching this path requires mp_get_package_nodes(X, ...) to return
a package_mask that does not contain X, which would itself be a bug.
But the current code silently produces an empty mask on a success
return with no way for the caller to distinguish it from a real
result.  Either document as a hard invariant that mp_get_package_nodes
always includes the queried node in its output, or fall back to
policy->nodes explicitly before the final goto out.

--- [RFC PATCH 3/4] mm/memory-tiers: register CXL nodes via initiator ---

> +static int cxl_region_find_nearest_node(struct cxl_region *cxlr)
> +{
> +	for (i = 0; i < p->nr_targets; i++) {
> +		cxled = p->targets[i];
> +		cxlmd = cxled_to_memdev(cxled);
> +		numa_node = dev_to_node(&cxlmd->dev);
> +		if (numa_node != NUMA_NO_NODE)
> +			return numa_node;
> +	}

For multi-target interleaved CXL regions, this returns the host CPU
NUMA node of the first valid target only.  If different targets are
attached to different sockets, the region ends up associated with only
one package.  Is there a reason not to pick the target whose host node
is nearest to the region's NUMA node, or to register the region against
all relevant packages?

> diff --git a/drivers/dax/kmem.c b/drivers/dax/kmem.c
> +	mp_probe_package_id(numa_node);
> +
>  	for (i = 0; i < dev_dax->nr_range; i++) {

mp_probe_package_id() fires the notifier chain before the memory ranges
are onlined via add_memory_driver_managed().  Inside the notifier,
cxl_region_add_package_node() calls
phys_to_target_node(cxlr->params.res->start) to match region_nid
against dax_nid.  Does phys_to_target_node() return a valid nid at
this point on all CXL bring-up paths, given that the memory has not
yet been onlined?  Please confirm the ordering is safe.
